animal.description:
Yeti is living in a foster home. Submit an application from our website and then make an appointment to meet her.

Yeti is not eligible for foster and will be a straight adoption.

Age: ~1 year
Weight: ~63lbs
Housebroken: Working on it! She needs to be on a strict schedule 
Crate trained: Working on it! Takes 10-30 minutes to settle and would benefit from continued training 
Dog sociability: Reportedly dog-friendly from prior shelter. Hasn't had close interaction with dogs in our care yet, but she seems excitable/friendly when she sees them from a distance on walks. May pull/jump when she sees them.
Cat sociability: Unknown
Kids: Unknown
Ideal home: Yeti is adaptable to many spaces, but would prefer to not live in an elevator/high-rise building. She is reported to be able to climb fences, so if she's in a home with a yard she needs to be monitored. She may do well with a dog pal in her home or access to doggy daycare.

Yeti is a mushy, sweet, calm, snuggly lady! She loves to curl up and nap on the couch but is always down for a frolic in the snow. She enjoys walks but can definitely settle down when you want to. She is so gentle and doesn't care about people being in her personal space. She warms up to new people very fast and loves quickly and loves hard! She is a lovely lady and her most favorite activity is just hanging out with you. 

Yeti's adoption fee is 300. She will be spayed on a future date (2/4/21) and a 50 refundable spay deposit will be required. She is up to date on core vaccines, microchipped and heartworm negative.

***We are receiving a much higher than usual number of adoption applications. We ask that you please be patient and someone will be in touch via email within 72 hours. Please do not email us unless you have not received a response in 72 hours. Please only fill out one adoption application. ***

animal.description:
Dante is a sweet boy who is bubbling over with a pure joy for just being alive. There’s rarely a moment where he isn’t enthusiastically wagging his tail or looking for someone to give kisses to. He loves his foster humans, and he is not shy at all at when it comes to loving any new human he meets, either. He will come right up to you and curl into your lap, and it will be love at first snuggle! 
He adores his foster fur-siblings and likes to roughhouse with them when it’s wrestle time, but he’s always ready to cuddle up with them for naps too. He loves going to the dog park to meet new friends, and he’s been an absolute darling to everyone he’s met so far. He’s great with all other dogs, and wonderful with kids. He has not been tested with cats yet, but we do know that he likes to chase birds. 
Dante was found in a rural area in Louisiana, and it doesn’t seem like he’s ever had any owners. He is working hard on learning how to potty train and sit. His ears go straight up when he know he’s a good boy, and down when he knows he did a naughty. He is eager to please and he loves treats. He needs someone who will be patient with him while he learns to be his best self. 
Dante’s exact age is unknown, but he’s estimated to be about 1 year. So while he might fill out a little, it’s unlikely he’ll grow too much past his dainty 25 pounds. His breed is unknown, but whatever his mix is, his foster family thinks it’s pretty perfect. 
If you are looking for an adorable best friend who is going to love you unconditionally and kiss you all day long, Dante is the guy for you!

Please note: as with most rescue puppies, we have no way to guarantee this puppy’s breed or size potential. 

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for puppies covers initial deworming,  puppy vaccinations, microchip, and spay/neuter at the rescue's approved vet at 6 months of age. Please see our website for more information.

2021 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

*Any breed labels used by Take Paws Rescue, its employees/volunteers, or on vet records provided cannot be guaranteed.  Breed labels are given based on information obtained during intake and/or best guesses based on appearance and/or temperament of the dogs and Take Paws Rescue gives no assurance to the accuracy of these labels. Labels are necessary for postings to many animal networking sites, such as Pet Finder, and are no way a guarantee. Additionally, exact age and potential size cannot be guaranteed.

If you would like to adopt this pet you can fill out an online adoption form at www.yakimahumane.org. Please give the name and ID number for the animal you wish to adopt.
If you are thinking about adding a pet to your family, be a hero, please consider adopting a shelter pet and if you already have pets – for life’s sake – spay and neuter. Spaying and neutering your pets is the single most important thing you can do to help decrease our nations severe pet overpopulation.
*NOTE: Nearly 90% of the animals that come into our shelter are abandoned, neglected, traumatized, injured, or ill. We attempt to give our best assessment of the animal’s welfare and temperament. animal.description:
++REQUIRES HOME WITH LARGE BREED DOG EXPERIENCE++

++ REQUIRES HOME WITH FENCED YARD++

NAME: Cody Carson

AGE/GENDER: 4 years old, Male

BREED: Ridgeback Mix

TEMPERAMENT: Active, sweet, playful

WEIGHT: 100 lbs

HOUSE TRAINING: Great!

CRATE TRAINING: Great!

OTHER DOGS: He really likes other dogs

CATS: No experience but based on his interest we feel a home without cats is best.

CHILDREN: Cody is nervous around children so he is not a candidate for a home with children.

ADOPTION DONATION: $425.00

HEALTH: Cody is neutered, microchipped, flea treated, dewormed, and is current on vaccines. Your adoption donation goes toward the cost of this vet care as well as other incidental costs of care.

HISTORY: Motley Zoo Animal Rescue was asked to find Cody a great forever family and that is exactly what we plan to do!

NOTES FROM CODY'S FOSTER HOME: Cody is a sweet, affectionate and well-trained boy who loves his people and playing ball. He is really an amazing dog- however, he is extremely fearful of new people and places. He tends to take cues from other dogs and we feel a companion dog in the home will help him, and he also needs a patient family so he can gain some confidence.

Cody is obedience trained, housebroken and fantastic in a crate, and will appropriately bark at strangers/ noises. When people come over however, he needs time to warm up- but throwing the ball expedites that process significantly!

This big boy looks so happy and comfortable when playing and this is one of the best ways to relax and exercise him.

Because of his lack of confidence and nervousness around strangers, he will need to be in an adult-only home that has prior strong breed experience and will need further training on his confidence (we have a class for that!).
Cody is not for a first-time dog owner.

We also feel he will not fare well in an apartment/condo/townhome setting and requires a fenced yard so he can play and run where he feels safe. We hope his new family will challenge his fears and help work him through them in time.

Foster Update: Cody is easy and sweet with those he knows, but he is VERY fearful and guarded with strangers, especially men. He has fully bonded with and trusts my husband and me- but he will require some careful oversight when visitors come and interact with him.

All dogs adopted from Motley Zoo come with a leash and Martingale collar (or a harness, if necessary), depending on each dog's particular needs.

ABOUT MOTLEY ZOO:

Motley Zoo Animal Rescue is a volunteer run, foster based, 501(c)(3) non-profit animal rescue organization based in Redmond, WA. Motley Zoo does not have a traditional shelter location, but instead, utilizes private foster homes which care for the animals individually, in a home environment, until a "furever" home is found.

Motley Zoo also runs "Rock Star Treatment" Dog Daycare & Services Studio in Redmond, WA which is a day-use facility and does not hold kennels of adoptable animals. The dogs there are owned animals who come to the facility while their families are at work and school so they can play and socialize in a safe environment. We dub this service our "Year-round" fundraising program which helps us support our rescue animals and the $15,000/ month vet bills we incur.

Please email adopt@motleyzoo.org and request an adoption application so we can get you started on the journey to finding a new, furry friend! Once you have been approved to adopt, then we can set up a meeting with the animal you have been matched with.

For more information, please visit www.motleyzoo.org.

Thank you for considering adopting a dog in need!

Woof,

The Motley Zoo Crew

animal.description: Everyone meet Bear! Bear is around 18 months old and a approximately 70 lbs. We believe Bear is an American Bulldog mix. Bear is a sweet affectionate pup who would love a forever home. He is great with people and other dogs, but really likes to chase cats, so he would do best in a no cat home with a secure yard. Bear has been in a house before and didn’t have any potty accidents, he’ll go in a kennel but doesn’t like to stay in it long or he’ll voice his opinion on the matter and whine or bark to be let out. Bear is up to date on all shots and preventative, heartworm negative, and will be neutered soon. His adoption fee will be $50, please let us know if you’d like to meet him.

animal.description:
Hello, I'm Milo! I am a 3 year old Terrier mix and I weigh 21lbs. My favorite things are scratches, cookies, and taking walks outside. If I was a dessert, I'd be a Mexican Hot Chocolate cookie...a sweet treat with a little spice. My perfect day would include a long walk outside in the sunshine followed by a good movie curled up on the couch with you. I'd love to have a family that will take me on adventures and love on me. If you like spirited sidekicks when we'd be a great team! 

I am good with some dogs, but I prefer females. A dog-to-dog meeting will be required so that I can meet my future brothers/sisters before going home! I would be best with children over 15 years of age and I am not a fan of being picked up/carried around. 

If you are interested in Milo, please fill out an adoption application online through our website, foothillshumanesociety.org.

Thank you for taking the time to view our adoptable pets. We have many loving animals that will make a great addition to your family. If you have any questions, please feel free to contact us. Email: pets@seagoville.us or call 972-287-6838.

All of our animals receive basic vaccinations and microchip upon intake. Dogs receive DHPP and Bordetella and cats receive FVRCP.

The adoption fee is $80 and includes intake vaccines, rabies, spay/neuter and microchip. If the animal has not already been spayed/neutered, you have 30 days, from the day of adoption or until the animal is 7 months of age, in which to provide proof of spay/neuter to the city. Also, be sure to check out our facebook page for up to date pet listings.

Seagoville Animal Shelter
1330 E. Malloy Bridge Rd.
Seagoville, TX 75159

Come visit at 15699 W. Aniceto Rd. Casa Grande, AZ 85193.  We are open Wed through Sun, 10 am to 4 pm.

animal.description:
This puppy is in Tennessee. Adoption Donation $250 if picked up in TN, $300 plus transport fee for out of state adoptions.

Isn't Hooch the most adorable little dude? Hooch has one very specific requirement for his adoption: to sleep in bed with his humans! This very good boy is a 10 week old, 7.2 pound, Pug/Cavalier mix (best guess), seeking a perfect fit for his forever family. Hooch is a happy boy who loves to play with other dogs and says having a dog friend in his new family would be ideal. He is working on leash and crate training, but needs your consistency and guidance to master these things. Hooch enjoys outside time, and is always ready for an adventure, so an active family would be best for him. Hooch is pretty chill for his age, and enjoys snuggle and cuddles after the long day of play. He loves stuffed animals, squeaky bones to chew, and the like. If you feel like Hooch is the perfect fit, apply to adopt today!

Interested in adopting? Take the first step and complete an adoption application on our website: http://aarf-tn.com/adopt/adoption-apps/

If you have questions that are not covered in the profile, visit the Pet Inquiry Form: http://aarf-tn.com/contact/pet-inquiry-form/.

THIS PET IS FOSTERED IN TENNESSEE! We do list and adopt our pets nationwide. Typical transport cost to the Northeast is $160. Due to interstate adoption regulations, we are not able to adopt to RI and MA state residents.

A.A.R.F. (All About Rescue and Fixin' Inc.) http://aarf-tn.com/ is a non-profit, 501(c)(3) no kill animal rescue organization located in the Upper Cumberland area of Tennessee. A.A.R.F. is comprised of unpaid volunteers and survives only on public donations. Thank you for thinking adoption first!

Prior to adoption, all canines and felines are spayed or neutered, have received their age appropriate vaccinations, have been de-wormed for common parasites, and have received treatment for prevention of fleas and ticks. All canines over the age of 6 months have been tested for heartworm. All canines are put on heartworm prevention as soon as possible - this means dogs as soon as they are tested negative. Puppies are put on prevention immediately. All felines, regardless of age, have been tested for Feline Leukemia/FIV. Each animal receives a health check by a licensed veterinarian prior to adoption. Anything else found will be treated by our organization prior to adoption.

My name is Courage, and I just transferred to HSU from an overcrowded shelter in Nevada. The staff named me Courage because that's what I'm trying to display in the face of my many recent life changes. I am still unsure about meeting new people, but once I warm up to someone, I'm a total cuddle bug. I like to sit in laps and guilt my people into remaining seated until I'm ready to wake up from my nap. I've done ok meeting other small dogs, but I may have never met a large dog, cat or kid, so I'll need slow introductions to all those. If you have the experience and patience to help a shy little scruffy blossom into a truly courageous boy, please take me home today.

animal.description:
Norman
DOB: September 9, 2018
Adoption Fee: $150.00
Norman is a male Lab/Beagle mix.

I am a quiet and shy boy. I would prefer a household with less commotion. I am best suited with children 12 years and older. I am nervous meeting new people, but with time to get to know one another I become very friendly quick.

I require a physically fenced in yard. I am not fond of a cable tie and not a fit for an invisible fence. I may match with another dog, pending a meet and greet. I am not looking for a playmate or to be a playmate. I would enjoy the company of another dog with a similar type personality as mine. I should be fine with cats, with a slow positive introduction.

I would enjoy daily walks after I have acclimated to my new home. I will be nervous with car rides but with the right introduction to it, I may learn to enjoy it. I am not a high activity guy, but do not mind a little excitement every once in a while.

K.C. is a female Wirehaired Terrier mix.

I am anxious at the shelter. I do not like all the commotion. I am a little nervous with men, but with the right family I should adjust. Otherwise, I am happy, energetic and affectionate.

I need some leash work, and would do best with a physically fenced in yard. I may have a bit of a prey drive; a fence would keep me contained. I may be too timid for an invisible fence, and I am not a fit for an apartment.

I am best suited with older children 10+. I may match with another dog pending a meet and greet. I have not greeted all dogs the best at the shelter and would be best suited with male dogs. I have not been fully tested with cats, but I do have a Terrier prey drive. Use caution.

I am very smart. In a home with less commotion around me, I should pick up on things quickly.

animal.description:
Randall is a male seven week old lab/shepherd mix puppy born approximately 12/14/2020. He comes from a litter of puppies that were being given away at days old when their mom stopped nursing due to an infection. A Good Samaritan helped them along until “The Big Three” (named after “This Is Us”) found their way to Take Paws. Randall has been dewormed and had his first round of puppy vaccines. He will be microchipped before going home. He will be neutered at 6months, which is covered by the rescue.
Randall is a playful explorer. He loves to find new toys, but also loves some chill, snuggle time with his foster mom or siblings. He has unique brindle stripes on the softest puppy fur. Eventually he will probably medium-large sized. He is working on crate training and using a potty pad. Randall can’t wait to be find his forever family and be part of an “us”! This sweetheart is ready for a forever home!

Please note: as with most rescue puppies, we have no way to guarantee this puppy’s breed or size potential. 

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for puppies covers initial deworming,  puppy vaccinations, microchip, and spay/neuter at the rescue's approved vet at 6 months of age. Please see our website for more information.

2021 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

*Any breed labels used by Take Paws Rescue, its employees/volunteers, or on vet records provided cannot be guaranteed.  Breed labels are given based on information obtained during intake and/or best guesses based on appearance and/or temperament of the dogs and Take Paws Rescue gives no assurance to the accuracy of these labels. Labels are necessary for postings to many animal networking sites, such as Pet Finder, and are no way a guarantee. Additionally, exact age and potential size cannot be guaranteed.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Name: Lennon
DOB: 5/23/20
Weight: 28 lbs
Adoption Fee: $450

Lennon who his foster family calls Lenny is the funniest, silliest little dude ever! While he should be sad and pouty having entered rescue not long ago with a crushed pelvis and mangled hip, nothing slows him down or wrecks his happy mood. Lenny is mister sunshine and rainbows and is always making everyone laugh with his antics. Even the sound of his voice and the way he talks back when you talk to him is funny. Lenny has a zest for life that some dogs might find annoying, so he would love to have another doggie friend in his forever home that is also playful and likes to wrestle and be silly. He has some herding breed in him so he tends to herd his people a little, so we think older kids would be best so he doesn't try to "shepard" any toddlers where they shouldn't be! He doesn't love being the kennel but will go in the kennel with treats and does quiet down if his doggie friends are kenneled next to him. He LOVES to eat and many times needs to be reminded which bowl is his, where his bowl is, to slow down, and/or that he still has food in his bowllittle ADHD! At night he loves to snuggle, which his foster mom loves. He loves all types of dog toys and will fetch and bring it back. He has learned to only chew on appropriate things now. He will carry the occasional shoe around the house, and just "deliver" it to one of his people without chewing on it, he thinks he is being helpful! He sleeps on a dog bed at night in his foster parents room and zonks out at night like a good boy. Sometimes you do have to watch out as he will sneak into the shower with you if you have a walk in shower, then your quick shower turns into a dog bath and shower for you! Lenny did have a Femoral Head Ostectomy surgery about a month ago to repair his hip and is currently working on some physical therapy to help that heal. He will most likely always have a bit of a wobble or limp in back, but that would not slow this guy down. He is truly one of a kind and everyone who has met him thinks he is hilarious when he gives them a little "woodpecker" with his nose to their leg when they are not paying attention to him!

*Physical Therapy is currently being done at Granite City Pet Hospital in St. Cloud*

In the meantime if you have questions or are interested in me, please fill out an adoption application at www.ruffstartrescue.org.

An adoption application is the best way to show your interest in an animal.

Please check out our website, www.ruffstartrescue.org for more details and additional pictures on any of our animals!

All Ruff Start dogs and cats are spayed/neutered, up to date on age appropriate vaccines, microchipped, dewormed, and on monthly flea/tick and heartworm prevention (dogs) as well as heartworm tested (dogs).

Ruff Start Rescue is a foster based rescue. Animals are located in homes throughout Minnesota. We do not have a facility where animals are kept.

Ruff Start Rescue Adoption Policies: http://www.ruffstartrescue.org/info/display?PageID=11744

animal.description:
Ranger is the most gentle giant you will ever meet! He is a big love bug, and an even bigger cuddler. He is friendly with children, and big and small dogs. He is not too hyper, but does enjoy playtime and going to the dog park with his foster brothers. He also does great at doggy daycare in playgroup! We don't know anything about Ranger's background, as we rescued him from a high-kill shelter in Texas. However, we do believe that he was hit in his past. We believe this because if you move at him fast, he flinches. We think it was likely by a man, as he is slightly more timid around some men. He is still very social though! It is so sad, and he is still the most trusting, loving boy that we have ever met! We would prefer Ranger to find an adopter who is a female, or a family with a female present, as he is much more comfortable around females! While he is still very friendly with men, he is visibly more timid around them. Despite whatever may have happened to him, he still loves all people. Ranger does not have a single aggressive bone in his body. He is the single most loving dog that we have ever met!

Ranger is likely a Lab/Boxer mix. With almost any rescue though, breed is just a guess! He likely has a bully breed in him, so cannot go in a home with breed restrictions. Ranger is around 1-2 years old. He really is SUCH a sweetheart with all people and dogs alike.

With any rescue, moving from a shelter to a foster to an adoptive home can be very confusing. When an adopting family is sensitive to the challenges of change and acclimation for these dog's, the transition is far easier. A home with a very loving and nurturing family that understands that blossoming takes time would be perfect home for a rescue dog. Socialization, pure love and belly rubs is a gift to a dog that is undergoing a life change. Given the time and space, these dogs shine.

Farfel's Rescue has found over time (we've rescued more than 3,000 dogs over 15 years of rescue) that families that attend level 1 group training classes or address individual challenges at home with one of our approved positive reinforcement/force free trainers keep their dogs for life. Dogs that do not get proper training and socialization have a much higher risk of developing behavioral problems. There is a bonding that occurs through the training process that can't be duplicated. It also teaches behaviors that enable a dog to go out into the world with excellent manners that create a very respectful relationship between dogs and their humans. It is for all these reasons that Farfel's isn't willing to adopt to a family that doesn't choose to create this training relationship. Farfel's is happy to provide a list of approved positive reinforcement/ force-free trainers in your area.

Ranger is up to date on his shots and neutered.

Ranger is available for adoption now! Applications are currently being accepted for our wonderful pup. If interested in this gorgeous, very cuddly/sweet and loving best friend, please fill out an application completely at http://farfels.com/farfels-rescue/adoption-form/ and submit.

**PLEASE NOTE** If you're truly interested in adopting from us, please be sure to fill out our Farfel's Rescue adoption application found at the link above or at farfels.com. Adoption site applications such as Petfinder, Rescueme and Adoptapet don't provide enough information and therefore aren't useful. Our Farfel's application is the only initial tool that we have to determine a great match for this very deserving puppy. We're sorry, but in most cases, we're unable to get back to those that don't submit our Farfel's Rescue adoption application. Thanks very much for choosing rescue.

animal.description:
Kevin is a male seven week old lab/shepherd mix puppy born approximately 12/14/2020. He comes from a litter of puppies that were being given away at days old when their mom stopped nursing due to an infection. A Good Samaritan helped them along until “The Big Three” (named after “This Is Us”) found their way to Take Paws. Kevin has been dewormed and had his first round of puppy vaccines. He will be microchipped before going home. He will be neutered at 6months, which is covered by the rescue.
Kevin is the biggest  of the siblings and a total love bug. His favorite things to do are snuggle, sleep, and eat (like any good puppy!). He has the absolute softest puppy fur! Eventually he will probably medium-large sized. He is working on crate training and using a potty pad. Kevin can’t wait to be find his forever family and be part of an “us”! This sweetheart is ready for a forever home!

Please note: as with most rescue puppies, we have no way to guarantee this puppy’s breed or size potential. 

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for puppies covers initial deworming,  puppy vaccinations, microchip, and spay/neuter at the rescue's approved vet at 6 months of age. Please see our website for more information.

2021 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

*Any breed labels used by Take Paws Rescue, its employees/volunteers, or on vet records provided cannot be guaranteed.  Breed labels are given based on information obtained during intake and/or best guesses based on appearance and/or temperament of the dogs and Take Paws Rescue gives no assurance to the accuracy of these labels. Labels are necessary for postings to many animal networking sites, such as Pet Finder, and are no way a guarantee. Additionally, exact age and potential size cannot be guaranteed.

animal.description:
King joined us with his packmates from our "Missouri 11" dogs taken into rescue after their lifelong owner passed away.

Like most of his former packmates, King has a great deal of formal training to his credit, but not a whole lot of life experience as a companion animal in a family home environment. He can be unsure of new people at first, but once he warms up to you, look out! He happily enjoys a good back rub and just hanging out on a comfy dog bed at home.

King would love a home with a dog buddy his size, but he is unknown around cats. He was bred to be a working dog and he is headstrong, so we recommend a home with no small children. Homes with older, GSD-savvy kids where supervision is the norm can be considered.

Unfortunately, King has tested positive for heartworm disease and will need to undergo treatment. He is currently intact but will be neutered once he has recovered from heartworm treatment. SGSDR covers all veterinary care costs for our dogs until adoption.

King is currently searching for his foster or foster-to-adopt home where he can get his treatment completed, learn about life in a family, and emerge healthy, happy, and well!

If you think King would be the perfect temporary or permanent member of YOUR family, please apply to foster or adopt.

Our Adoption Fees:
-------------------

*Dogs and puppies 12 months old or younger: $400

* Adult dogs over 12 months of age: $350

* Senior dogs over 7 years of age qualify for our "Seniors FUREVER" program! Seniors are special to us, so we offer two options: 

(1) If your heart has a special place for the seniors, you can adopt a senior dog for the regular adoption fee of $350 and this becomes a perpetual fee. You can adopt another SGSDR senior dog at any time from us in the future at NO CHARGE. 
(2) If you aren't sure about your future adoption capacity, you may adopt your SGSDR senior dog for a reduced adoption fee of $250.

For more information on adopting a Serendipity dog, please visit our website at any of the following links:

http://serendipitygsd.org/adopt
http://serendipitygsd.org/adopt/faqs
http://serendipitygsd.org/adopt/seniors 

Visit us on Facebook for regular updates on all of our program dogs!  https://www.facebook.com/SGSDR/

***Petfinder inquiries will not be answered. Please visit our website for more information on how to meet adoptable pets and how to submit an adoption application***

We are available to show adoptable pets, to approved applicants and by appointment only. Available appointment times fill up quickly so please visit our website and follow the instructions regarding visits and adoption practices.
 
INTERESTED IN MEETING AND/OR ADOPTING OUR ADOPTABLE PETS? 

TO ENSURE THE SAFTEY OF OUR COMMUNITY AND STAFF AND TO UTILIZE OUR LIMITED TIME TO INTRODUCE FOLKS TO ADOPTABLE PETS AS EFFICIENTLY  AS POSSIBLE WE ARE ONLY SCHEUDLING APPOINTMENTS TO MEET ADOPTABLE PETS WITH PRE-APPROVED APPLICANTS. TO PRACTICE SOCIAL DISTANCING EFFECTIVELY WE ARE ASKING THAT ALL INTERESTED PARTIES MAKE AN APPOINTMENT TO MEET OUR ADOPTBALE PETS. 

HAVING A PRE-APPROVED APPLICATION DOESN'T OBLIGATE YOU TO ADOPT FROM US AND IS FREE! PLEASE VISIT OUR WEBSITE AT WWW.ELMORESPCA.ORG  TO FILL OUT AND SUBMIT AN ADOPTION APPLICATION ELECTRONICALLY.

WE ARE ASKING FOLKS TO GIVE US A 3-7 BUSINESS DAY WINDOW TO PROCESS APPLICATIONS AS WE ARE RECEIVING SO MANY! YOU WILL RECEIVE AN EMAIL TO SCHEDULE AN APPOINTMENT AS SOON AS YOUR APPLICATION IS PROCESSED. 

WE ADVOCATE FOR OUR WARDS AGGRESSIVELY UNTIL AN APPROVED APPLICANT, WHO IS A GREAT MATCH, VERBALLY COMMITS TO ADOPT THAT PET.  

***Have an approved adoption application on file? Please email info@elmorespca.org, indicate that you have an approved adoption application, let us know what name under which the adoption application was submitted, and that you would like to schedule an appointment to meet adoptable pets. 

***** Scooter is a sweet heart of a dog who was rescued from high kill situation in Monroe County in Georgia. These folks work tirelessly to help dogs in need of help Northward to their new beginning! Scooter is nine pounds of adorable and is a lover! The first thing we noticed about Scooter is that he walks on the leash like a show dog who loves to prance. He has wonderful manners and is friendly with cats and people. He likes to puff up when he sees another dog, but we think that is mostly all show. We introduced him to the cats in the cat room and he ignored each of them! Scooter is a lover who is very dramatic and dainty. He despises the snow, he hates his paws to be wet and he loves to be inside. This little love is adorable and will do well in most homes with submissive pets. He is current on vaccinations, has tested negative for heartworm, ehrlichia, lyme and anaplasmosis and has received a clean bill of health from several vets. He is scheduled to get neutered on 2/3/21 at Palmer Vet Clinic and will be able to go home after that. This little guy is a chihuahua mix through and through. He has the most mournful bark and bray... it almost sounds like a skeksis from the dark crystal or a velociraptor! He quiets down after a few minutes in his kennel, but if he sees his person he will let you know that he upset about being left alone.  This little guy has got some pipes, but he is lovable, adorable and compact!   We'd love to help Scooter find his perfect match.

animal.description:
Carlton came to us from a NC shelter where he sat for months with no interest. He came into the shelter back in September with a neck wound likely from an embedded collar. He also has an old injury to one of his back legs. Possibly an old fracture. It's healed and does not cause him any pain at all. It doesn't slow him down one bit!

Carlton has not had a great life so far but, that doesn't stop him from loving EVERYONE he meets! We took him to a big Volleyball tournament where there were hundreds of people and he had the absolute best day of his life!! He loves to meet people and wants to give everyone kisses. He sucked up all the attention he could.

He is housebroken and crate trained. He knows a few basic commands such as "sit" and "down". He loves car rides, balls, bones and a soft bed. He is very strong and working on leash manners. He does great with other dogs his size. He's very interested! We have not introduced him to smaller dogs yet. 

This is a great dog looking for a best friend. He's obviously not been cared for much of his life but, we're gunna change that.

He is neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, heartworm negative and on prevention.

Adoption Fee: $300

***We require a complete and approved application before setting up a meet n greet.***

To apply to adopt just copy and paste the link into your search bar!
https://fs24.formsite.com/oneatatimek9rescue/form1/index.html

animal.description:
Kate is a female seven week old lab/shepherd mix puppy born approximately 12/14/2020. She comes from a litter of puppies that were being given away at days old when their mom stopped nursing due to an infection. A Good Samaritan helped them along until “The Big Three” (named after “This Is Us”) found their way to Take Paws. Kate has been dewormed and had her first round of puppy vaccines. She will be microchipped before going home. She will be spayed at 6months, which is covered by the rescue.
Kate is probably the shyest of the siblings and a total love bug. She has the softest, fluffy fur. Her favorite spot is cuddled up on her foster mom or in a puppy pile with her brothers. Eventually she will probably be on the larger side of “medium”, but for now she is the smallest of the litter. She is working on crate training and using a potty pad. Kate can’t wait to be find her forever family and be part of an “us”! This sweetheart is ready for a forever home!

Please note: as with most rescue puppies, we have no way to guarantee this puppy’s breed or size potential. 

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for puppies covers initial deworming,  puppy vaccinations, microchip, and spay/neuter at the rescue's approved vet at 6 months of age. Please see our website for more information.

2021 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

*Any breed labels used by Take Paws Rescue, its employees/volunteers, or on vet records provided cannot be guaranteed.  Breed labels are given based on information obtained during intake and/or best guesses based on appearance and/or temperament of the dogs and Take Paws Rescue gives no assurance to the accuracy of these labels. Labels are necessary for postings to many animal networking sites, such as Pet Finder, and are no way a guarantee. Additionally, exact age and potential size cannot be guaranteed.

animal.description:
Timothy was found stray and never redeemed. He is about 10 years old and only weighs 18lbs. Timothy tested high positive for heartworms so we found an amazing foster home that would get him through treatment. He's now done with treatment and ready for a home of his own. 

His foster reports he's crate trained but has had a few accidents in the house but he was on prednisone for heartworm treatment which can sometimes increase urination so most likely a side effect of that. He is good with other dogs, unsure of cats and he needs a calmer home so a home without small children is best. 

Timothy must be fed separately as he has some food aggression. It's okay to give him treats around others but he gets a little exuberant at meal times, so it's best he eats in his crate alone or in a separate room. Sometimes when dogs aren't used to getting what is needed for their care, they can develop these tendencies. He doesn't mind eating in his crate. 

His foster mom says he needs a calm and patient home as he has likely been abused and neglected, but with patience he enjoys attention and is highly treat motivated. He is not yet confident on a leash but needs a securely fenced yard because he has been on crate rest and his foster mom hasn't had him out on a leash very often.

animal.description:
Meet two-year-old and 13 pound terrier Alex. He can be shy at first but as soon as he trust you he is your best friend and wants to be in your lap. He’s very dog friendly and would make a great second dog. He can be needy and is desperate for love. He’s doing well so far on house and crate training. He enjoys going for walks playing in the yard and lots of lap time he would make a great active companion

Thank you for reading about our awesome dog. All dogs came to us from different situations and we often do not know much about their past, but they are rescue dogs who deserve a second chance and need patience on their journey. All of our dogs our are in foster homes all across the bay area. 

The first step of the process is you must submit an application in order to set up a meet and great or talk with the foster family. Once application is submitted the foster parents will contact you to chat more about the dog and make sure they're a good fit and can answer any further question. The application answers most of all of our questions and can best match you. If you do not get the dog you apply for we can use your same application for 90 days towards another dog in our care and simply forward your app to that foster parent. 
http://form.jotform.com/underdogca/dog-adoption-application

All dogs will be fully vetted (Spay/ Neutered, Micro chipped, DHPP and Rabies Vaccinated) and other possible vet care prior to adoption.

The adoption fee is $350 which is considered a non refundable donation

visit us at underdogca.com or follow us on FB and IG @underdogca
https://www.facebook.com/underdogCA

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Name: Millie

DOB: 4/1/2017

Weight: 40 lbs

Adoption Fee: 375.00

Miss Millie came into rescue about 10 months ago from Houston, Texas. While we don't know exactly what life was like for Millie, we do know that in her short 3 or 4 years, it was not good and people were not nice to her. Millie is what we would like to call a work in progress. Everyday she gains a little bit of confidence in herself, in the people around her and in her ability to just be a dog. Over the last 10 months in her foster home she has gone from a completely shut down and scared dog that only hid in the back of her kennel for days at a time to a dog that learned to initially trust her pack of dogs in the home. The dogs have shown her what to do with dog toys, how to run laps around the backyard, why its cool to bark at squirrels when they run up the trees and how to wrestle with them. Her current foster home does bring in new foster dogs and Millie does require slow introductions and needs her space while acclimating to the new dog. She likes to take meeting new dogs on her own terms and rambunctious puppies are not her favorite. That being said, having a dog or two in her forever home that can take her under their wing and continue to guide Millie on her path to confidence as a dog is key to her success and happiness.

People is where it gets tricky for Millie. Her foster family spent months gaining her trust just to be able to touch her. She is still unable to be put on a leash, when she sees a leash she panics. She does love to be near her people now. She wants to be in the same room with everyone and will even sit near on the couch. She likes to sleep on a dog bed in her foster parents room at night with her foster siblings. Millie LOVES comfort if there is a pillow, blanket or soft spot on the couch, she will find it and burrow into the spot. When she is in just the right mood and everyone is calm, she will allow her foster mom and sometimes foster dad to rub her belly and scratch her face and ears. She will even flop onto her back, but it is always on Millie's time and at her pace. She always needs to be approached at her level and never from above her. She loves to be told how pretty she is and her foster family thinks she even smiles when they give her compliments! She is very food motivated, girl LOVES to eat. She is still working on taking treats from someone's hand, but she knows the sound of the fridge opening, the crinkle of the cheese wrapper or the dog treat container opening and comes running.

Millie likes to play outside with her doggie friends and will come to the back door when called. When she comes back into the house she will want her person to step out of the way so that the doorway is clear for her and no scary people are in the way! She has many quirks and many of them are manageable and then many of them may start to go away as she continues to come out of her shell. She still loves her kennel, but no longer hides in it. She knows the command Kennel and will "kennel" when asked to. She also knows "sit" and we have been working on "place". A trainer has come out to Millie's foster home to work with her and will continue to invest time into Millie to get her on the right track to be successful in a forever home

Please check out our website, www.ruffstartrescue.org for more details and additional pictures on any of our animals!

All Ruff Start dogs and cats are spayed/neutered, up to date on age appropriate vaccines, microchipped, dewormed, and on monthly flea/tick and heartworm prevention (dogs) as well as heartworm tested (dogs).

Ruff Start Rescue is a foster based rescue. Animals are located in homes throughout Minnesota. We do not have a facility where animals are kept.

Ruff Start Rescue Adoption Policies: http://www.ruffstartrescue.org/info/display?PageID=11744

animal.description:
Annie / Female / Approx. 2 years / 29 lbs / Beagle Mix / Mississauga

Meet Annie! Annie is described as a sweet, calm and gentle companion that loves to be with her people. When not curled up at your side, her new favorite activities include napping, playing with her toys, running/playing in the backyard and going for walks. She gets so desperate for pets she will climb on you if she has to! She is the ultimate snuggly buddy and is always looking for warm places to sleep. She is in tune with her humans and often looks to them for guidance but can be stubborn at times. She has a classic beagle howl when encouraged by other dogs or even the tv!

Annie is nervous around new people and will generally tuck her tail between her legs when they approach. She is never aggressive but her body language suggests she prefers some space. After one week in her foster home she had warmed up to all members of the household. She will need multiple meetings with new people before she is fully comfortable. Annie has not spent any time with kids but seems to be very interested in them. Based on her personality, we think Annie would probably do well with respectful kids ages 10+.

Annie is medium energy and currently enjoys a shorter walk in the morning, lunch time walk and a one-hour walk in the evening. On leash she walks well but true to her breed she loves to sniff! Her family should allow her to follow her nose and/or introduce scent games at home to stimulate her mind. She does have a bit of a drive for small animals like rabbits though so she should be kept on leash at all times.

Although she is never left for more than a couple of hours, Annie is crated when her people go out. She did rip up her bed once when alone and so again, it’s important her family is home often and willing to help her overcome her anxiety. At night Annie will settle in her crate or on a bed next to yours so long as she can see you. Usually at most she takes 15 minutes to settle. She likes to shred things like newspaper and cardboard so for the time being, will need supervision or a puppy proofed space.

Annie is very intelligent but she is not treat or toy motivated. She will need support with basic obedience and learning some more commands. Annie would prefer a family who is home more often than not. She can likely adapt to any home environment but would appreciate a backyard to run, sniff, and enjoy the outdoors. She is fearful of loud or unexpected noises, so would prefer to be outside of the downtown core.

If you’re interested in adopting Annie please apply at https://www.fetchandreleash.ca/adoption-info#adoption-form

Annie’s adoption fee is $800. To learn more about our adoption fees and the adoption process, please visit our FAQs at https://www.fetchandreleash.ca/about-us#about-faqs.

animal.description:
Klaus is a goofy, boisterous, happy, and mischievous boy! He's incredibly curious and likes to run and explore. Klaus came into rescue underweight and suffering from ear infections and aching hips, but since he's been in rescue and getting plenty of good care, love, and expert veterinary attention, this boy is blooming!

He's up to about 70 pounds now and still needs more weight, so he is definitely a big boy. Klaus can be a bit of a bull in a china shop and needs an outlet (or several!) for him to burn off his energy. He's not your typical senior and has the energy of a much younger dog. 

He is learning to play with the other dogs in his foster home and would do best with at least one companion dog to keep him company. Klaus is a sweet but headstrong boy and will need a firm but gentle hand to lead him. 

His hips do seem to bother him from time to time, but he's improving, and he loves nothing more than to be rubbed and scratched there. He does fine on stairs and navigating the couch, but on occasion needs a little help getting into and out of taller climbs like up into the car.

This boy will do anything for the right treat and praise from his humans. He loves food (don't leave anything within reach, he may help himself) and is eager to please. He shows no signs of food or toy aggression. He was very interested in cats upon arrival to his foster home but has adjusted and, while still curious, respects that kitties are friends, not food.

We recommend a home where Klaus has easy access to a fenced yard and he would love to have a dog buddy (or kitty!) as well. He's proven good with his foster family's teenage daughter, but is unknown with small children.

Klaus is a sweet boy with all the benefits of a senior with the energy and drive of a younger dog, perfect for families ready for a dog with established personality (and does he have plenty!) and still energy for fun.



Our Adoption Fees:
-------------------

*Dogs and puppies 12 months old or younger: $400

* Adult dogs over 12 months of age: $350

* Senior dogs over 7 years of age qualify for our "Seniors FUREVER" program! Seniors are special to us, so we offer two options: 

(1) If your heart has a special place for the seniors, you can adopt a senior dog for the regular adoption fee of $350 and this becomes a perpetual fee. You can adopt another SGSDR senior dog at any time from us in the future at NO CHARGE. 
(2) If you aren't sure about your future adoption capacity, you may adopt your SGSDR senior dog for a reduced adoption fee of $250.

For more information on adopting a Serendipity dog, please visit our website at any of the following links:

http://serendipitygsd.org/adopt
http://serendipitygsd.org/adopt/faqs
http://serendipitygsd.org/adopt/seniors 

Visit us on Facebook for regular updates on all of our program dogs!  https://www.facebook.com/SGSDR/

animal.description:
We are accepting adoption applications for Eva but she will not be able to go home until after her spay is done on Feb 23rd. This will also give Eva's prospective adopter(s) time to come and meet her a couple of times as she is a little on the shy side. Adopter MUST have a physically fenced yard due to Eva's shy nature. 

This beautiful girl is Eva and she is a 1 1/2 year old Catahoula Leopard dog mix who weighs 45 pounds. Eva came to us from an abusive situation with one of her puppies (who has been adopted!) and was very standoffish and scared of everyone but especially of men. It took us several weeks to gain Eva's trust and get her to a point where she was comfortable being handled. She has been with us for almost 3 months now and has made amazing progress and has even done super well with meeting new people! 

Eva is a super sweet and energetic girl who loves to be pet and to give kisses once she is comfortable with you! She loves to run and play in the yard and chase tennis balls as well as find sticks to chew on! Once Eva really starts to trust you she will roll over for belly rubs and will let you rub her belly for hours. 

We believe that Eva would do well in a home with children as she seems to really open up to them but would of course need to meet any children in the home before the adoption was approved. We haven't had the opportunity to have Eva around dogs that were not her puppy but believe that she would do well with them and will need to meet any dog in the potential adopters home to make sure everyone gets along. We also haven't had the opportunity to test Eva with cats but can certainly do that if a prospective home has cats. 
Eva's last owner told us she was housetrained and she does really well in her kennel with only an occasional accident at night. She does now the command sit and walks pretty well on a leash when she is wearing a harness! She also seems to enjoy riding in vehicles!

If you would like to set up a time to come meet Eva please give us a call at 641-774-5113 as we are open by appointment only. 

If you would like to donate towards Eva's care please go to the top of this page and click on the Sponsor button. You will then be redirected to her Petfinder Sponsor/Donation page. Any amount is greatly appreciated!

Eva's adoption fee is $75.00 and that does include all of her Vet work.

animal.description:
Keeper

Keeper could not have a better name - he really is a keeper. He is an amazing dog just looking for his forever bed to crash in! He’s a low energy dude just looking for someone to snuggle and love him for the rest of his life. And give him Costco bones.?

Keeper will be five in March. his entire world was shattered when his mom died in September and then his dad died in January. In six months, keeper lost everyone he knew and loved. This has caused some stress and depression in this handsome boy.

Because of the trauma he went through, he would do better in a home with older kids that can understand he will need some time to settle in. he is fine with children of all ages but his current foster home has 2 preschool age boys that can be a little overwhelming.  Even though Keeper tolerates it pretty well, we would like to find the best fit for him.

4 year old male Pitbull Mix?

Size: Large (60+ lbs)

We only adopt pets within 4 hours of Reno

All current pets in the household MUST be spayed/neutered and current on shots (yes, we do call and verify this information)

Attendance at a professionally run obedience course is a requirement of adoption! 
We do not adopt out dogs as gifts

I need some work on leash training but my foster mom says a Gentle Leader harness will help me learn!
If you're a Lab lover, then pick me, because I'm your Lover Lab and I'm looking for a date for Valentines Day!
xoxo Kingston

I am currently awaiting to be neutered, but I am available for meets until the big day happens, which is very soon!!

Completion of an Adoption Application via our website (www.RescueCrew.org) is the best way to show your interest in an animal and is the first step in the adoption process.

All companion animals adopted by The Rescue Crew are spayed/neutered, up-to-date on age appropriate vaccinations, tested for FIV/FeLK (cats) or heartworm (dogs), microchipped, dewormed and provided with monthly flea/tick and heartworm preventatives.

The Rescue Crew is a foster based rescue organization, meaning all of our adoptable pets are located in homes throughout Minnesota. We do not have a physical location where you can stop by to visit the animals - we require the completion of an Adoption Application prior to meeting any of our adoptable pets in foster care.

For the most complete information regarding this animal, and all of our adoptable pets, please ensure you are visiting our website directly at www.RescueCrew.org. You can also access the necessary online adoption application here as well.

animal.description: If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out the Dog Pre-Adoption Survey. With any further questions please call our Brunswick Campus at 207-449366 ext. 206 or 207. Dear Santa, My name is Scarlett and what I want most this year is a new home for the Holidays! Don't get me wrong, I really like it here at the shelter, but I have been here since last February and I am really ready to find my new family and start my next adventure! I love to play with toys and once I get to know you, I can really be a love! I just want a friend to love me and snuggle on the couch. The outside world and new people scare me a little so you will have to be patient. I do have behavior friends at Midcoast Humane who can help me with my fears and adjust in my new home so don't worry too much. We will work through my fears together. Children do scare me a little, so I prefer human adults, please. I have been so good with other dogs, but please no cats. Do you know of a home for me? Love, Scarlett

animal.description: Hi, my name is Willow! I 'm a beautiful girl looking for a home where I can be the only animal. I 'm smart and willing to learn for the humans in my life and I have a lot of energy (mental and physical!) and will need a home where I can safely burn that energy off! I would love a home with a fence so that I can run free, but it isn 't a requirement. I am very friendly when meeting new people and loved my stuffed toys! I 've done well with kids in the past, but if there are children in the home, I 'd prefer them to be 15+ years old, and I need to meet them prior to adoption. If you are interested in adopting me, please go to the adopt tab and fill out a Dog Pre-Adoption Survey. I look forward to barking with you!

animal.description: If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out the Dog Pre-Adoption Survey on midcoasthumane.org. With any further questions please call our Brunswick Campus at 207-449366 ext. 206 or 207. Dear Santa, I'm Momo and I am the happiest girl around as long as you play ball with me! I really like to hang out with you at home but ohh I don't like other animals at all! They really scare me! When I was younger, I lived up North and was a guard dog, but I really didn't like that job. I just want a quiet place to call home with no kids or other animals. My own yard and fence would be "the bee's knees", so I never meet those scary off leash dogs anymore! They are so rude! I really do love everyone at the shelter, especially Tammy, but I have been here for almost a year and I really want to find my own home before the holiday. Do you know of a home for me? Love, Momo

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Pratt! I'm a 30lb terrier mix that is currently looking for a foster home. I'm cautious of new people, and am especially scared being on leash. I'm hoping that I can get into a home with someone that would be willing to work with me, and help me learn about the world. I like the people at the shelter, and I don’t mind when they pet me, and really like it when I get to have treats! I’m comfortable enough to give face kisses, but all these loud noises are a bit much for me. I hope that I can find a foster to stay with to help me build some confidence in the world so I can become the perfect friend for someone. 

Please let the people at SWCHS know if you think you have a good home for me to stay at. I'd prefer no other animals, but if there is another clam dog that is ok. No young children under the age of 14 please, and it would be best that I be in a house rather than an apartment. A fenced in yard is required, as I can run off when I get frightened.

Apply for foster at www.SWCHS.com or call 715-423-0505

animal.description:
Manilla is a happy and sweet female Beagle/Boxer` mix. She was born on 12/12/2020. She is expected to be a medium dog with an athletic build. She has a medium energy level. A fenced yard is a must for this bouncy girl.

Manilla is fun-loving and cuddly too. She loves to hang with her people and play with her toys. She is seeking a family to have adventures and also snuggles on the couch. She currently lives at a foster home in Spindale, NC and is ready to go to a loving home on 2/12/2021.

The adoption fee is $300.00 and includes deworming, vaccinations, flea treatment, and local spay voucher at our clinic location. To adopt go to https://www.leeshorerescue.com/apply.html and fill out an application to adopt a puppy.

AAS

animal.description:
Chap

We will never understand what possesses people to dump senior dogs. Chap is AWESOME! He is happy, playful, chill, loves EVERYONE and just needs a loving home to live out his senior years.

Are you looking for a mellow, loving companion? Look no further and fill out an adoption application today!

Breed: Boxer   
Age: 10+ years
Size: Large
Gender: Male????

Good with:
Dogs: Yes
Kids: Yes
Cats: Yes

For more information and pictures, or if you're interested in adopting me, please visit:  www.boxersandbuddies.com.  All of our dogs are FAMILY COMPANIONS!

Our adoption requirements are:

We only adopt pets within 4 hours of Reno
You must be 21 years of age
All current pets in the household MUST be spayed/neutered and current on shots (yes, we do call and verify this information)
We do not place female boxers with other female dogs
Attendance at a professionally run obedience course is a requirement of adoption! 
We do not adopt out dogs as gifts

animal.description:
This sweet girl is Lacie Shortz! Lacie is an 8 week old tan and white female lab mix who was released to the shelter along with her siblings because they could not find homes for them all. Lacie is quite scared at first but doesn't mind being handled by the staff. Lacie would do well in a home with other pets since she is so young and would be a great companion for the kiddos! animal.description:
Hello!  My name is Roxy,  and I'm a female mixed breed born in November of 20xx.   

My adoption fee is $175.

Hanover Humane will only be adopting me to a home in Hanover County, Virginia or a locality that is part of the Richmond, Virginia metropolitan area.

I'm a sweet, shy girl who, once I'm comfortable, will play and have a good time. I also like my down time and will lay quietly on my bed and chew on my nylabone. I'm not that great on leash, so you'll have to work with me on that. I love to have my ears scratched, and I adore it when you kiss my forehead. My biggest vice is that I like to chew up my toys, bedding, and blankets. I even had to have surgery to remove a blockage from my intestines when I accidently ate part of my blanket.  My new owner will have to be vigilant and make sure I don't get into anything like that that I can tear up.

 I've been neutered/spayed, am current on all of my vaccinations (DHLPP, Bordetella and Rabies), tested for heartworms (and am negative) and put on heartworm preventative, and microchipped.  My new owner will receive a month of free pet health insurance at adoption. 

If you are interested in me or want to meet me, please submit an adoption application at www.hanoverhumanesociety.org and you will be contacted to make an appointment.

animal.description:
Trinity

Trinity had a rough start. Untrained and unsocialized, her family brought home a new puppy. Trinity was eating when the puppy tried to eat out of the same bowl. Dogs don't know how to share - it's not in their genetic makeup. Trinity did what most dogs would do - she guarded her food and bit the puppy.

The family decided to get rid of Trinity. We have since tested Trinity with a variety of dogs - she is fearful at first, but, when given appropriate introductions and some time to adjust, she is off and playing.

We wish people understood that introductions - especially when bringing a new dog into a current dog's home, need to be done gradually and positively to be successful. We know Trinity is a good dog that just needs some time and training.

Checkers can be easily startled and her flight instinct is very high, the best home for her would be a more quiet laid back type of home. A fenced in yard would also be a huge positive for her new family. 
Checkers has never been around children, so our concern is that she could scare by the excitement and unpredictability of young children. Older more mature children would be a better fit.
Checkers is fully vaccinated and microchipped;. She has an appt for her spay on March 8th.

animal.description:
Meet Henry, a three and a half-month-old Rottie/Shepherd mix.

Henry is an active, outgoing boy who loves to play. He was found with a lab mix named Harley and although they get along well together they are not a bonded pair and can be adopted out separately. Henry is all puppy, so get ready for a rodeo clown! Please remember that Henry is a puppy and puppy behavior comes with the package. They need basic training and potty training along with being provided chew toys to encourage proper chewing habits. All puppies require socializing from a young age to help them become the best, most well-rounded dog they can be.

Henry will be available for adoption on 2/3/2021 at 5:01 PM.

If you are interested in adopting this pet please fill out an adoption questionnaire at www.yakimahumane.org. A Yakima Humane Society staff member will contact you once your questionnaire has been received.


If you would like to adopt this pet you can fill out an online adoption form at www.yakimahumane.org. Please give the name and ID number for the animal you wish to adopt.
If you are thinking about adding a pet to your family, be a hero, please consider adopting a shelter pet and if you already have pets – for life’s sake – spay and neuter. Spaying and neutering your pets is the single most important thing you can do to help decrease our nations severe pet overpopulation.
*NOTE: Nearly 90% of the animals that come into our shelter are abandoned, neglected, traumatized, injured, or ill. We attempt to give our best assessment of the animal’s welfare and temperament. Unfortunately, due to lack of funding, volunteers, and resources our physical and mental assessment of the animal is not always 100% correct.

,Due to COVID-19, all adoptions will be by appointment only. To adopt, complete our online adoption application and an Adoption Counselor will contact you within 48-hours to schedule your adoption appointment. Adoptions for any pets in foster will be completed offsite at our PetSmart Claiborne location on a case by case basis. The safety of our foster parents and community is of utmost importance to us and it will be at the foster's discretion if they'd like to meet at this time. Thank you for choosing adoption! 

This very sweet girl is friendly and loves affection.  She has no experience on leash but walks nicely.  She would love to find a home where she can share her life with a loving human family.

To inquire about an adoptable animal from the Louisiana SPCA, please call 504.368.5191, ext. 150 to speak with an adoption counselor.
To see more adoptable animals from the Louisiana SPCA, please go to http://la-spca.org/adopt.



The petfinder.com system requires that we choose a predominant breed or breed mix for our dogs. Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.

animal.description:
Adoption Fee: $450
 Transport Fee: $160

Allie is roughly around 14 weeks. She is a sweet girl who is very active, smart, and would love to go on walks. We are currently working on house training and crate training. She is a playful girl who is looking for a family of her own and a home full of toys. 

Our adoption fee includes the spay/neuter, up to date vaccines, microchip, Interstate Health Certificate, and the transport service to get the new family pet to you. 

 Note: All dogs are located in foster homes in ALABAMA and will be transported NORTH AFTER ADOPTION. This means there is no way for a meet and greet before adoption. We try our best to give you honest personalities of the pup for you. We are more than happy to send videos, pictures, and even video chat so that you may have the connection with your pup before adoption. Please know that we can only guess breed and age of our rescues.

 All pets are delivered by a licensed transporter. 
The transportation company that we use is PETSLLC. They are well known and very professional. The link is listed, you are more than welcome to look and see what the closest drop off location is for you. 

http://www.petsllc.net/stops.php?route=9

 COMPLETED APPLICATIONS TAKE PRECEDENCE OVER INQUIRIES! If you are interested in adopting, the FIRST step is to complete an application!

 Please copy and paste the following URL for our adoption application:

 https://fs29.formsite.com/pickenscountypartnersforpets/form1/index.html

 Please be advised that our volunteers are busy rescuing, transporting, and caring for our animals. We will respond to your application as soon as possible. Upon review of your application, the rescue in Alabama will contact you, so you can ask any specific questions that you may have. 

 If there is more than one decision maker in the home, all of them should be in agreement.

 We do not adopt to anyone under the age of 21.

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Pax! I'm a 1 year old, 30lb terrier mix that is currently looking for a foster home. I'm very scared of new people, noises, and especially being on leash. I'm hoping that I can get into a home with someone that would be willing to work with me, and help me learn about the world. The people at the shelter are so nice, and I've become comfortable enough to let them pet me, and lay with me. I know that I can be the perfect dog if I could have someone work with me consistently in a calm environment. 

Please let the people at SWCHS know if you think you have a good home for me to stay at. I'd prefer no other animals, but if there is another clam dog that is ok. No young children under the age of 14 please, and it would be best that I be in a house rather than an apartment. A fenced in yard is required, as I can run off when I get frightened.

Please apply at www.SWCHS.com to be a foster, or call 715-423-0505

animal.description:
Audrey is cute as a button and has a personality to go with it. She loves to snuggle with you or play with other dogs. Gets along with everyone she meets. Has a permanent head tilt which makes her that much more adorable. The vet thinks it is a vestibular issue which meds did not help but she doesn't let it slow her down. When I pick her up she leans to that side so when you put her down she doesn't go on her feet she lays down. I carry her with her head on my shoulder to offset the tilt so she does not feel off balance.

She does great in her crate at night and is keeping it clean.

She is one of the keeper pups that has you rethinking how many dogs is to many.

She is a 5 month old, 20 lb hound mix.

animal.description:
Meet Kay, a one-year-old Siberian Husky mix.

Kay is a happy, athletic girl weighing in at 58 pounds. She will "sit" for treats and it appears as though she has had some training. This girl walks well on a leash and is very curious, she loves to sniff around and explore. Kay would make a great jogging or hiking buddy for someone. Please do your breed research before applying to adopt Kay, Huskies and Husky mixes are a very special breed of dog with unique requirements. They require a securely fenced backyard as they often have the inclination to roam and can be great escape artists. They need active homes that will help them burn off some of that extra energy along with a home that will work with them and help them learn and maintain their manners as huskies can have a tendency to be stubborn and mouthy at times. Huskies can have strong prey drives, and while every dog is different, many huskies will chase cats and livestock. Grooming is also an important part of their routine, brushing them several times a week can help prevent their undercoat from matting and keep them looking their best. Huskies are a fun, active breed that many have fallen in love with over the years, but please keep their breed needs in mind if considering adding one to your household.

Kay will be available for adoption on 2/3/2021 At 2:17 PM.

If you are interested in adopting this pet please fill out an adoption questionnaire at www.yakimahumane.org. A Yakima Humane Society staff member will contact you once your questionnaire has been received.

If you would like to adopt this pet you can fill out an online adoption form at www.yakimahumane.org. Please give the name and ID number for the animal you wish to adopt.
If you are thinking about adding a pet to your family, be a hero, please consider adopting a shelter pet and if you already have pets – for life’s sake – spay and neuter. Spaying and neutering your pets is the single most important thing you can do to help decrease our nations severe pet overpopulation.
*NOTE: Nearly 90% of the animals that come into our shelter are abandoned, neglected, traumatized, injured, or ill. We attempt to give our best assessment of the animal’s welfare and temperament. Unfortunately, due to lack of funding, volunteers, and resources our physical and mental assessment of the animal is not always 100% correct.

animal.description:
**PLEASE NOTE - FRAN AND MAX ARE A BONDED PAIR AND MUST BE ADOPTED TOGETHER. ADOPTERS INTERESTED IN FRAN AND MAX MUST HAVE DOG EXPERIENCE AND A FENCED-IN YARD**

Fran is an 8 year old spayed female German Shepherd Dog who weighs about 75 lbs. Fran and her boyfriend, Max, were rescued from a high kill shelter after their owner tragically died in a car accident. Sadly, these two beauties were part of a backyard breeding operation and were not given the care or attention they deserved for most of their lives. They are the sweetest pair who don't ask for much to be happy. After being forced to produce litter after litter of puppies for her entire life, Fran was battling a horrible case of pyometra when we rescued her. We were so glad we were able to provide her the care and surgery she needed in time. Fran also experiences some age-related weakness in his hind end, but she gets around just fine! As long as Max and Fran have each other, they are happy! They enjoy spending their days taking naps on comfy dog beds and exploring the yard. They are looking for a home with a fenced-in yard that they can romp around in and a family that is experienced with larger breed dogs. These senior couple would do best in a home where they can spend their days on one floor, as they do not navigate stairs very well. We absolutely adore this special pair, and we cannot wait to find them a wonderful home where they can spend their golden years - TOGETHER!

animal.description:
**PLEASE NOTE - MAX AND FRAN ARE A BONDED PAIR AND MUST BE ADOPTED TOGETHER. ADOPTERS INTERESTED IN MAX AND FRAN MUST HAVE DOG EXPERIENCE AND A FENCED-IN YARD**

Max is a 10 year old neutered male German Shepherd Dog who weighs about 72 lbs. Max and his girlfriend, Fran, were rescued from a high kill shelter after their owner tragically died in a car accident. Sadly, these two beauties were part of a backyard breeding operation and were not given the care or attention they deserved for most of their lives. They are the sweetest pair who don't ask for much to be happy. To add to their heartbreaking story, Max is said to have been shot in his front left leg, and he does sometimes drag that leg. Our vet checked him out, and it doesn't seem to cause him any pain or discomfort. Max also experiences some age-related weakness in his hind end, but he gets around just fine! As long as Max and Fran have each other, they are happy! They enjoy spending their days taking naps on comfy dog beds and exploring the yard. They are looking for a home with a fenced-in yard that they can romp around in and a family that is experienced with larger breed dogs. These senior couple would do best in a home where they can spend their days on one floor, as they do not navigate stairs very well. We absolutely adore this special pair, and we cannot wait to find them a wonderful home where they can spend their golden years - TOGETHER!

Interested in adopting? Take the first step and complete an adoption application on our website:https://www.all4pawsrescue.com/
